We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The patient’s symptoms suggest a possible ovarian tumor, and the histologic examination suggests a granulosa cell tumor. Granulosa cell tumors can secrete estradiol, so the most likely laboratory value that was increased at the time of presentation is Estradiol. Lactate dehydrogenase and α-fetoprotein are tumor markers for other types of tumors, while β-human chorionic gonadotropin is a marker for gestational trophoblastic disease.

The symptoms and ultrasound findings suggest an ovarian mass with the histologic exam showing the presence of primordial follicles, which suggests granulosa cell tumor. Granulosa cell tumor is known to produce estrogen, so the most likely increased laboratory value is Estradiol. None of the other options are typically increased in granulosa cell tumor.

We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The patient’s symptoms and the histologic examination suggest a diagnosis of ovarian cystadenoma, more specifically a serous cystadenoma. These tumors secrete estrogen, which can cause breast tenderness and menstrual irregularities. Estradiol is the most probable laboratory value to be increased in this patient. Lactate dehydrogenase, α-fetoprotein, and β-human chorionic gonadotropin are unlikely to be elevated in this case.

We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The patient’s symptoms and ultrasound findings suggest a possible ovarian cyst, and the histologic examination confirms the diagnosis of a follicular cyst. Follicular cysts are functional cysts that form from ovaries that fail to rupture and release an egg. These cysts can produce estrogen, leading to breast tenderness and menstrual irregularities. Therefore, the laboratory value that is most likely increased in this patient at the time of presentation is Estradiol. Lactate dehydrogenase, α-fetoprotein, and β-human chorionic gonadotropin are not related to ovarian cysts or follicular cysts.
